  "local_port": 58230,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Last year my Thanksgiving turkey was dry, what is the best way to roast a Thanksgiving turkey?",
  "response": "Roasting a perfect Thanksgiving turkey requires attention to preparation, cooking technique, and timing. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to ensure your turkey is juicy and flavorful:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Choose the Right Turkey**\n- Plan for **1 to 1.5 pounds of turkey per person**.\n- For easier cooking and even doneness, consider a **smaller bird** (12\u201314 pounds) or spatchcocking (butterflying) a larger one.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Thaw Properly**\n- If using a frozen turkey, thaw it safely in the refrigerator: **24 hours per 4\u20135 pounds**. For example, a 12-pound turkey takes about 3 days.\n- Avoid thawing at room temperature to prevent bacteria growth.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Brine the Turkey**\n- Brining ensures juiciness. Use either a **wet brine** (submerge the turkey in a saltwater solution with herbs and spices) or a **dry brine** (coat the turkey with salt and refrigerate uncovered for 12\u201324 hours).\n- For a wet brine: Dissolve **1 cup of kosher salt** and **1/2 cup of sugar** per gallon of water. Add aromatics like peppercorns, bay leaves, garlic, and citrus.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Pat the Turkey Dry**\n- After brining, pat the turkey dry with paper towels. This helps the skin crisp up during roasting.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Season Generously**\n- Rub the turkey inside and out with softened butter or olive oil mixed with herbs (thyme, rosemary, sage) and spices (salt, pepper, garlic powder).\n- Add aromatics like onion, garlic, lemon, or herbs to the cavity for extra flavor.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Truss or Don\u2019t Truss**\n- Trussing (tying the legs together) can help with even cooking, but it\u2019s optional. Leaving the legs untied allows more airflow for crispy skin.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Roast at the Right Temperature**\n- **Low and slow** method: Roast at **325\u00b0F (163\u00b0C)** until the internal temperature of the thickest part of the thigh reaches **165\u00b0F (74\u00b0C)**, about **15 minutes per pound**.\n- **High heat method**: Start at **450\u00b0F (232\u00b0C)** for 30 minutes, then reduce to **350\u00b0F (177\u00b0C)** until done. This creates a crispier skin.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Use a Thermometer**\n- Insert a meat thermometer into the thickest part of the thigh (without touching bone). The turkey is done at **165\u00b0F (74\u00b0C)**. The breast should be an additional 5\u201310 degrees less to prevent overcooking.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Baste (Optional)**\n- Basting with pan juices can add flavor, but it\u2019s not necessary for juiciness. Opening the oven frequently can lower the temperature and extend cooking time.\n\n---\n\n### **10. Let it Rest**\n- Remove the turkey from the oven and tent it loosely with foil. Let it rest for **20\u201330 minutes** before carving. This allows the juices to redistribute, keeping the meat moist.\n\n---\n\n### **Bonus Tips**\n- **Stuffing**: Cook stuffing separately to avoid undercooked turkey or soggy stuffing.\n- **Basting with Butter**: Apply butter under the skin for extra moisture and flavor.\n- **Spatchcocking**: Butterflying the turkey reduces cooking time and ensures even cooking.\n\n---\n\nBy following these steps, you\u2019ll achieve a juicy, flavorful, and perfectly roasted Thanksgiving turkey!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
